    <stitle>CALIPER DISC BRAKES - CALIPER</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcsubsec>
        <title>CALIPER</title>
        <svcsubsecinfo>
            <para>The caliper assembly is positioned on the anchor plate against machined surfaces. A caliper support
                key is installed between the trailing edge of the caliper and the anchor plate, with a support spring
                inserted between the key and caliper. A key retaining bolt keeps the support key from sliding out of the
                anchor plate assembly (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0401604">Figure 4</hotlnk>and
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0401605">Figure 5</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0401604" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0401604" filename="../figg04/G0401604.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 4. Exploded View of Single Piston Caliper Assembly (Code 04145)</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. OUTBOARD PAD AND LINING</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. INBOARD PAD AND LINING</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. CALIPER SUPPORT KEY</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. SUPPORT KEY RETAINING BOLT</callout1>
                    <callout1>5. CALIPER SUPPORT SPRING</callout1>
                    <callout1>6. CALIPER ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                    <callout1>7. PISTON</callout1>
                    <callout1>8. DUST BOOT</callout1>
                    <callout1>9. PISTON SEAL</callout1>
                    <callout1>10. BLEED SCREW</callout1>
                    <callout1>11. ANCHOR PLATE</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f0401605" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0401605" filename="../figg04/G0401605.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 5. Exploded View of Two Piston Caliper Assembly (Codes 04144, 04146, 04237, 04238)
                </caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. OUTBOARD PAD AND LINING</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. INBOARD PAD AND LINING</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. SHIELD</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. DUST BOOT</callout1>
                    <callout1>5. PISTON</callout1>
                    <callout1>6. SEAL</callout1>
                    <callout1>7. CALIPER HOUSING</callout1>
                    <callout1>8. TUBE SEAT INSERT</callout1>
                    <callout1>9. BLEEDER SCREW</callout1>
                    <callout1>10. ANCHOR PLATE (BRACKET)</callout1>
                    <callout1>11. SUPPORT SPRING</callout1>
                    <callout1>12. SUPPORT KEY</callout1>
                    <callout1>13. SUPPORT KEY RETAINING BOLT</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <para>The inner pad assembly is positioned with both ends confined within the anchor plate.</para>
            <para>The outer pad assembly is designed to locate on the formed machined outboard portion of the caliper.
                Therefore, the inboard and outboard pads are not interchangeable. (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0401604">Figure 4</hotlnk>and
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0401605">Figure 5</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>The outboard pads on the 2.88 inch bore caliper have a left and right hand side. This is due
                        to the beveled leading edge (or rear edge) of the pad material. Also, pads are marked left and
                        right side.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </svcsubsecinfo>
    </svcsubsec>
